SIMPLE: friend
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Friend
<hw>Friend</hw> <pr>(fr⟦ecr⟧nd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>frend</ets>, <ets>freond</ets>, AS. <ets>fre⟦oacute⟧nd</ets>, prop.
p. pr. of <ets>fre⟦oacute⟧n</ets>, <ets>fre⟦oacute⟧gan</ets>, to love;
akin to D. <ets>vriend</ets> friend, OS. <ets>friund</ets> friend,
<ets>friohan</ets> to love, OHG. <ets>friunt</ets> friend, G.
<ets>freund</ets>, Icel. <ets>fr⟦ae⟧ndi</ets> kinsman, Sw.
<ets>fr⟦aum⟧nde</ets>. Goth. <ets>frij⟦omac⟧nds</ets> friend,
<ets>frij⟦omac⟧n</ets> to love. ⟦root⟧83. See <er>Free</er>, and cf.
<er>Fiend</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who entertains for another
such sentiments of esteem, respect, and affection that he seeks his
society and welfare; a wellwisher; an intimate associate; sometimes, an
attendant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Want gives to know the flatterer from the <qex>friend</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>friend</qex> that sticketh closer than a brother.</q>
<rj><qau>Prov. xviii. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One not inimical or hostile; one not a foe or enemy;
also, one of the same nation, party, kin, etc., whose friendly feelings
may be assumed. The word is some times used as a term of friendly
address.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Friend</qex>, how camest thou in hither?</q> <rj><qau>Matt.
xxii. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who looks propitiously on a cause, an
institution, a project, and the like; a favorer; a promoter; <as>as, a
<ex>friend</ex> to commerce, to poetry, to an
institution</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>One of a religious sect characterized by disuse of
outward rites and an ordained ministry, by simplicity of dress and
speech, and esp. by opposition to war and a desire to live at peace with
all men. They are popularly called Quakers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>America was first visited by <qex>Friends</qex> in 1656.</q>
<rj><qau>T. Chase.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A paramour of either sex.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>A friend at court</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>A
friend in court</b></col></mcol>, <cd>one disposed to act as a friend in
a place of special opportunity or influence.</cd> -- <col><b>To be
friends with</b></col>, <cd>to have friendly relations with.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧He's . . . <xex>friends with</xex> C⟦ae⟧sar.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To make friends with</b></col>, <cd>to become
reconciled to or on friendly terms with.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Having now
<xex>made friends with</xex> the Athenians.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Jowett
(Thucyd.).</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Friend</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Friend
<hw>Friend</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Friended</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Friending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To act as the friend of; to
favor; to countenance; to befriend.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fortune <qex>friends</qex> the bold.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Friended</ent>⟦br⟧
